<HEADLINE>
FT  14 FEB 92 / Former Bestwood chairman accused of theft
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR TONY COLE, former chair-man of Bestwood, the industrial and property
holding company, appeared at City of London Magistrates' Court yesterday
charged with false accounting, perjury and thefts totalling more than Pounds
1.1m.
Mr Cole was arrested on Tuesday by City of London Police working in
conjunction with the Serious Fraud Office. The SFO has been investigating
the affairs of Bestwood since 1990, when the case was referred to it by
inspectors from the Department of Trade and Industry.
The DTI began investigating the company and Atlanta Fund Managers, one of
its former subsidiaries, in June 1989.
Mr Cole faces 13 charges, including five of theft. One charge involves
Pounds 212,305 allegedly taken from Atlanta Fund Managers, and routed to the
Swiss account of a Jersey company, Mamro Ltd, with which he was connected.
Two allege the theft of Pounds 300,000 from the trustees of the pension fund
of British Drilling and Freezing, another Bestwood subsidiary, and two
allege the theft of Pounds 602,500 from Bestwood itself.
He is also charged with stealing share certificates for 450,000 shares in
Aitken Hume International, the financial services group, belonging to
Atlanta Fund Managers.
He faces other charges that he concealed his connection with Mamro from
Bestwood's auditors, and committed perjury by concealing the connection both
during a High Court hearing and while giving evidence to DTI inspectors.
Mr Cole was remanded on bail of Pounds 150,000 until March 19 on condition
that he surrendered his passport, did not apply for travel documents, did
not travel outside Essex or Greater London, and reported to a police station
twice a day.
Four other people were charged last year as a result of the SFO
investigation into Bestwood and are awaiting trial at a Crown Court.
They are Mr Charles Wilkinson, of London, a senior partner in solicitors
Lawrence Graham, charged with offences under section 395 of the Companies
Act 1985; Mr Jeremy Colson, a financial director, of Nadderwater, Devon, on
similar charges; Mr Peter Southgate, an accountant, of Colchester, Essex, on
charges of theft, aiding and abetting an unauthorised loan, and false
accounting; and Mr William Collins, a stockbroker, of Egham, Surrey, charged
with theft and false accounting. Mr Southgate and Mr Collins face joint
charges with Mr Cole.
Mr Cole bought into Best-wood, which then had little more to its name than a
printing subsidiary and a stake in a drilling company, in early 1985 and
became chairman soon afterwards.
Between 1985 and 1988, he built it up by acquiring substantial stakes in a
number of companies. He created a mini-conglomerate with interests ranging
from drilling, contracting and property development to motor bike financing.
Bestwood, which suffered heavy losses after the 1987 stock market crash,
went into receivership in April 1990.
</TEXT>
