<HEADLINE>
FT  14 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Ministers move to prevent register
 -Council tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE POWER of local author-ities to canvass residents will be restricted by
the government in amendments to the council tax bill to be published today.
The move reflects government concern that the council tax should not be
accompanied by a register as the poll tax was.
Though some local authorities have warned that a register will be needed to
enable them to administer the largely property-based tax, the decision to
limit the ability to question residents was taken after consultation with
the local authority associations.
Mr Michael Portillo, local government minister, said the amendment would
stop authorities setting up a council-tax register by using their existing
powers under the Local Government (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1976, which
enables them to survey owners and occupiers in their areas.
Instead, they would be able to seek information only about who in each
household was the person liable to pay the tax and ask households to say if
they qualify for discounts.
Ministers emphasised that local authorities would not necessarily need to
make both inquiries of every household, since they would already have a good
deal of information. They suggested that many councils might wish to make
the inquiries only where they had to pursue non-payment.
Proposed changes in the bill will also enable the government to make
regulations putting beyond doubt the use of computer evidence in cases of
non-payment of the poll tax.
The bill will be discussed by the Lords at the beginning of next week and is
expected to become law early in March.
Mr John MacGregor, leader of the Commons, brushed aside protests from
opposition MPs yesterday at the government's decision to impose a guillotine
on the local government bill which extends compulsory competitive tendering
and sets up a commission to review the structure of local government. The
move will ensure that the bill can become law within the next few weeks.
</TEXT>
