<HEADLINE>
FT  14 FEB 92 / UK News (Employment): BP to derecognise two unions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BP CHEMICALS is to end collective pay bargaining at its Baglan Bay plant in
south Wales in a rare example of a large UK company derecognising
blue-collar unions.
The company's plan, announced yesterday with proposals to cut 130 jobs and
change working practices at the 900-strong plant, sparked fears among unions
that other BP plants would follow.
Many companies have withdrawn collective bargaining from white-collar
employees, but it is unusual for manual-worker unions to be derecognised.
BP Chemicals yesterday gave 90 days' notice to the TGWU general workers'
union and the AEU engineering workers of its intention to end their role in
pay bargaining at Baglan Bay. The two unions said that about 700 of the 900
workers on the site were their members. BP Chemicals said terms and
conditions of all employees would be harmonised, and each would be asked to
sign a personal contract.
Pay would depend in part on individual performance, although initially
workers would receive basic pay rises of up to Pounds 1,300 a year and
improved allowances.
Mr Fred Higgs, TGWU national secretary, said: 'It is extremely cynical for
the company to try to end collective bargaining at the same time as
announcing job losses. It is an attempt to intimidate people into giving up
their fundamental trade union rights. If they get away with it at Baglan
Bay, they may try it at other sites.'
The TGWU said it was seeking legal advice on the company's move. A meeting
of union officials throughout BP Chemicals has been called for Monday to
discuss industrial action.
Baglan Bay is one of three large chemicals plants owned by BP in the UK, the
other two are at Grangemouth near Falkirk and Hull. It owns a further dozen
smaller plants. The company proposes to alter shift patterns, increase team
working and train workers to take on a greater variety of jobs.
Mr Alan Bilsland, works general manager, said the changes were essential to
improve the plant's competitive position.
</TEXT>
