FT  14 FEB 92 / UK News (Employment): Theft of computer data reported
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PRISON Officers Association suggested yesterday that four thefts of
sensitive computer information from its north London headquarters fitted the
pattern of break-ins suffered by the three main political parties.
The union said it believed the thefts, which started last August, could not
be dismissed as coincidence.
Stolen information included details of staff arrangements at prisons in
Northern Ireland and at Brixton in south London, procedures for handling top
security prisoners, and addresses of those sympathetic to the union,
including MPs.
Mr John Bartell, the union's chairman, has written to Mr Kenneth Baker, home
secretary, drawing his attention to the burglaries and the 'lack of police
coverage' which made further incidents 'a distinct possibility'.
Mr Barry Sheerman, a Labour home affairs spokesman, has tabled three Commons
questions to the home secretary urging an inquiry into the thefts.
'The thefts coincide with an extraordinary series of attacks on the POA
including the forthcoming opening of Britain's first private prison,' said
Mr Sheerman.
Mr David Evans, the association's general secretary, suffered a burglary at
his home in August. Family memorabilia were stolen, but the association said
it viewed the break-in as suspicious.
The disclosures follow revelations that MPs have suffered a spate of thefts,
some apparently aimed at sensitive computer information.
Mr Paddy Ashdown, leader of the Liberal Democrats, was forced to make a
public statement about his private life after the theft of a confidential
document from his solicitor.
The 37-strong ruling general executive council of the TGWU general union has
moved slightly further to the left after the latest elections.
The left-right balance is now thought to be 23-14. Two of the territorial
seats have been abolished, taking out a right-winger in the northern region
and the leftwing dockers' leader Mr Walter Greendale from the Hull area.
</TEXT>
