<HEADLINE>
FT  14 FEB 92 / Repossessions of homes climb 72% to record: Slackening in
recruitment sustains unemployment - Fewer mortgage defaulters likely to be
evicted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE number of homes repossessed by mortgage lenders because their owners
could not keep up with monthly payments reached 75,540 last year.
The total, by far the highest recorded, was 72 per cent up on 1990. It was
slightly below forecasts of 80,000, however, and the rate of increase in
repossessions slowed in the second half of last year. The Council for
Mortgage Lenders indicated yesterday that the worst might be over.
Mr Mark Boleat, director-general of the council, said it was impossible to
predict how many people would lose their homes this year. He added ,
however: 'We expect a declining trend during the course of the year.'
The council believes the decline in eviction rates reflects the fall in
mortgage interest rates and an increase in the provision of advice from
lenders.
In spite of the slowing in the rate of repossessions the number of borrowers
more than six months in arrears was 275,350 at the end of the year. There
were 91,740 borrowers more than 12 months in arrears, compared with 59,690
half way through 1991. There were also 183,610 borrowers between six and 12
months in arrears, up from 162,210 in the middle of the year.
These borrowers are all at risk of having their homes repossessed,
suggesting that repossessions will remain at very high levels this year and
next.
Woolwich Building Society, one of the largest mortgage lenders, said
yesterday, however, that the number of its customers less than six months in
arrears was now the lowest for four years. Its more serious arrears cases
had also stabilised.
The council expects about 40,000 homes to be saved as a result of a package
of measures agreed between lenders and the government just before Christmas.
These measures include the direct payment to lenders of social security
payments for mortgage interest and the provision of Pounds 1bn for mortgage
rescue schemes by lenders.
Leeds Permanent, the sixth-largest building society, yesterday became the
latest lender to launch a rescue package. It will spend Pounds 100m on a
scheme under which the society will take a share in the value of a house and
provide the borrower with a reduced mortgage payment. The interest rate for
such borrowers will be capped at 9.9 per cent for five years.
Mr Mike Blackburn, Leeds Permanent chief executive, warned that there could
be no quick cure for the repossessions problem. 'A full recovery will take
at least two years to achieve and will depend on factors beyond our
control,' he said. He added that the decline in the number of new arrears
cases was by far the most important development.
National Westminster Bank, the only high-street clearing bank to put up
funds for a mortgage rescue scheme, launched a Pounds 30m mortgage rescue
scheme yesterday. The number of repossessed homes for sale will continue to
depress the housing market for some months. At the end of last year lenders
still had 67,370 repossessed homes on their books after selling more than
47,000 properties in the year.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
