FT  14 FEB 92 / Midlands air route to US urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS and DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MIDLANDS MPS yesterday pressed Mr Malcolm Rifkind, transport secretary, to
give American Airlines special permission to operate daily services between
Birmingham and Chicago.
The politicians, led by Mrs Maureen Hicks, Conservative MP for Wolverhampton
North East, said the Midlands business community was anxious to see daily
transatlantic services from Birmingham. These are ruled out in the existing
UK-US bilateral air agreement. The MPs want Mr Rifkind to relax the rules.
Talks between UK and US officials start in Washington on Monday to review
the agreement.
British Airways has rights to operate a service from Birmingham to the US
but does not believe such flights would be profitable.
American Airlines is also seeking a licence to operate transatlantic flights
from Nashville, Tennessee, to London Stansted.
BA said yesterday it did not object to the UK granting rights to US carriers
to operate provincial services in Britain, provided UK airlines were offered
'something worthwhile' in return.
BA has urged that future air agreements with the US should be negotiated at
a European level, rather than on a bilateral basis.
Mr Robert Crandall, chairman of American Airlines, warned in Dallas this
week that the recession was prompting increasingly protectionist moves by
governments to shield their national carriers.
'I fear there will be more protectionism from governments over the next
year,' he said, singling out the UK government for preventing his airline
from flying between Chicago and Birmingham and between Nashville and
Stansted.
US carriers have also become concerned by the tougher attitude being adopted
by France and Germany to their bilateral agreements with the US.
</TEXT>
