<HEADLINE>
FT  14 FEB 92 / Redwood challenges critics of Lloyd's structure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER, DAVID OWEN and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN REDWOOD, corp-orate affairs minister, yesterday hit out at Labour
calls to bring the Lloyd's of London insurance market under an independent
regulatory regime.
Speaking in response to allegations that Lloyd's syndicates had been
favouring working Names within the market by offloading bad risks on to
outside Names, Mr Redwoood said that advocates of change would first have to
demonstrate there had been 'failings' under the present structure. Names are
the individuals whose assets provide Lloyd's capital.
Mr Redwood accused Ms Marjorie Mowlam, Labour's City affairs spokeswoman, of
'jumping too many hurdles all at the same time' when calling for Lloyd's to
be brought within the terms of something similar to the Act which regulates
the rest of the City.
He suggested that if concerns about the malpractices were serious enough the
Names should take them to the Serious Fraud Office. But he added that there
was not enough evidence to suggest that a change in the market's regulatory
regime was needed.
The claims had been made by a group of Names, including Conservative MPs,
and prompted calls for an investigation in four parliamentary early day
motions by two Labour MPs, Mr Brian Sedgemore and Mr Dennis Skinner.
Earlier a delegation of Names, including Mr Paul Marland, Conservative MP
for Gloucester West, met Mr Redwood. It included the chairmen of three
action groups for syndicates suffering heavy losses as a result of
catastrophe claims, as well as Mr Marland, who was a member of syndicates
managed by Rose Thomson Young and Gooda Walker until his resignation from
Lloyd's early this year.
One member said Names on the catastrophe syndicates were facing losses of
more than Pounds 500m. The suggestions in the early-day motions that working
Names were being given preferential access to some better-performing
syndicates were dismissed as an 'unwarranted slur' by Mr David Coleridge,
chairman of Lloyd's.
Mr Coleridge said a recent report on Lloyd's by a market task force had
shown that in two of the last three underwriting years external members had
enjoyed higher re-turns than working members.
Insider syndicates - those on which working Names predominate - listed in
the the Labour motions were 45 (managed by the Bankside agency), 138
(Bailey), 179 (Anton), 183 (Ashley), 372 (Claremount), 431 (Wren), 960
(Sturge), 990 (Morgan), 994 (Kellett) and 1028 (Wellington). Four of these,
(179, 183, 990 and 1028) returned losses in 1988 (the last year for which
final figures are available).
According to Chatset, the group that provides independent analysis of
Lloyd's syndicates, over the most recently available six years only two of
the named syndicates (45 and 960) were among the top performers.
Mr Anthony Cooper, managing director of Wellington Underwriting, which
manages Syndicate 1028, said he was 'mystified and shocked' that one of the
his agency's syndicates was included on the list.
</TEXT>
