defying a curfew to support a pro-independence march from the Pakistani side
of the disputed Himalayan region.
Police said 4,000 demonstrators stoned security forces trying to enforce the
indefinite curfew, imposed on Monday before the march started.
Pakistani troops this week thwarted volunteers of the Jammu and Kashmir
Liberation Front (JKLF) from crossing from the Pakistan-ruled part of
Kashmir into the region controlled by India.
In Muzaffarabad, Pakistan, Mr Amanullah Khan, the JKLF leader, said he had
called off the march to avoid further loss of life. At least three people
were killed by police shooting on Wednesday amid pitched battles between
militants and Pakistani security forces. 'They told us frankly that anybody
who today, tomorrow or the day after tries to cross their barrier would be
shot,' Mr Khan said.
Pakistan banned the march because it feared an incursion along the United
Nations-monitored ceasefire line could lead to another conflict with India,
which had ordered troops guarding the line to let no one across.
