<HEADLINE>
FT  14 FEB 92 / Manufacturing falls to 1988 levels
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES, LESLIE COLITT and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN, BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE end of Germany's unification boom has pushed orders for west German
manufactured goods and plant utilisation in factories back to mid-1988
levels, according to figures from the Ifo economics institute in Frankfurt.
Industrialists expect stagnation 'at best' for the coming months, the
institute says, and they are increasingly doubtful that use of existing
capacity will reach 'satisfactory' levels in the year ahead. Investment
goods makers, for example, which are now working at 84.8 per cent capacity,
expect continuing contraction.
The new data and opinions, assembled by Ifo from its regular business
surveys, suggest that hopes of improvement depend more on increased overseas
demand than any domestic upswing.
The delicacy of the economic balance is underscored by a claim from the DIW
institute in Berlin that west Germany's real gross national product fell by
half a percentage point in the last quarter of 1991. If confirmed, this
would be the third decline in succession.
'The latest industrial orders figures show that the western economy is going
through a difficult phase,' DIW says in a report today. The institute, a
recognised authority on east Germany, also claims that real GNP in the east
fell 30 per cent last year, compared with the hitherto accepted estimate of
20 per cent.
The correction stems partly, it says, from the discovery that increases in
construction industry output have been 'clearly over-estimated'.
Construction is one of the main motors driving the eastern economy towards
officially forecast growth of 10 per cent this year.
The DIW also accused the Treuhand privatisation agency of increasing
liquidity loans to its ailing east German companies this year instead of
using the money to modernise and restructure them.
The institute said the Treuhand should stop guaranteeing liquidity loans to
companies which were using them for 'uncontrollable purposes'. Instead,
investment loans and company capitalisation should be increased - up to a
fixed limit - and be tied to the level of non-guaranteed bank loans obtained
by companies. They should also have to achieve profitability by a set date.
According to the DIW, DM9.9bn, nearly a third of the Treuhand's budget, went
toward restructuring its companies last year, while DM4.5bn was spent on
guaranteed liquidity loans. These were largely used to pay wages, salaries
and other running costs. This year the Treuhand plans to guarantee DM8bn in
liquidity loans while boosting restructuring funds to only DM11.5bn, said
DIW.
It proposed that, instead of subsidising wages, the Treuhand should give
decreasing wage subsidies for a limited period to companies which are to be
restructured. It also suggested that old debts of companies be cancelled and
transferred to the federal budget. Both Bonn and the Treuhand recently
suggested that the east German state governments might want to invest in
large companies which could not otherwise be rescued. But the governments
themselves almost totally depend on funds from Bonn which faces a myriad of
financial demands from east Germany.
IG Metall union officials yesterday dropped a threat of mass protests
against a merger of Fried. Krupp and Hoesch after a last-minute deal with
Krupp giving workers 10 seats on the 20-seat supervisory board of the
enlarged steel group, Reuter reports from Bonn. The board will not have a
further 'neutral' member as other steel concerns do.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
