<HEADLINE>
FT  14 FEB 92 / Recession drives Ford to record Pounds 920m loss in UK
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FORD, the US carmaker, suffered a record Pounds 920m loss on its ordinary
activities in the UK last year.
The figure, before extraordinary gains, includes losses of Pounds 450m
associated with Ford's takeover two years ago of Jaguar, the UK luxury car
producer, and compares with a loss of Pounds 274m a year earlier.
Hit by the recession and steep fall in new car sales in the UK, Ford of
Britain's net loss for the year was Pounds 590m after taking account of
Pounds 330m of extraordinary gains.
Of this, Pounds 290m came from the transfer of ownership of Jaguar to its US
parent company last November and Pounds 40m from the sale of its loss-making
Ford New Holland tractor operations to Fiat of Italy.
The heavy losses announced yesterday have forced Ford of the US to pump
Pounds 390m into Ford of Britain to shore up the UK company's balance sheet.
Ford of the US has injected Pounds 100m in new equity capital, with the
remainder coming through the Jaguar transfer.
Excluding Jaguar, Ford of Britain fell to a loss on ordinary activities of
Pounds 470m last year from a Pounds 61m profit in 1990.
The scale of the losses by Ford, the UK new car market leader, will
intensify the pressure from UK carmakers on the government to take urgent
action in next month's Budget to stimulate car sales.
Mr Ian McAllister, Ford of Britain chairman and managing director, insisted
yesterday that the company was not 'playing politics' by bringing forward
publication of its results from the normal date of mid-May. However, he said
that 'we do think that the government should take action to stimulate the
market'.
New car sales in the UK have plummeted by 31 per cent in the past two years,
while commercial vehicle sales have fallen by 43.7 per cent.
The speed of the decline in UK new vehicle demand and the depth of the
recession took Ford by surprise. Ford vehicle stocks climbed to unacceptable
levels last year, forcing it into an expensive price war.
Worldwide, Ford plunged into a net loss of Dollars 2.258bn last year from a
net profit a year earlier of Dollars 860m, according to results announced
yesterday.
The US recession and competition from Japanese carmakers have hit American
producers hard. Chrysler last week announced a net loss for 1991 of Dollars
795m, compared with a net profit of Dollars 68m in 1990. General Motors, the
world's biggest vehicle maker, is expected to announce losses of several
billion dollars later this month.
Ford of Europe's automotive operations, including Jaguar, slumped to a
Dollars 1.079bn net loss last year from a Dollars 145m net profit in 1990
and a Dollars 1.19bn profit in 1989.
