<HEADLINE>
FT  14 FEB 92 / International Company News: Western Mining dives into the
red
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE JACQUES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WESTERN MINING Corpora-tion, the Melbourne-based nickel, gold and aluminium
group, dived into the red in the first half to December following a ADollars
20m (USDollars 14.9m) write-down of its mining assets.
The company yesterday reported an interim turnround to a ADollars 60.5m net
loss from a ADollars 141.9m net profit on a 15 per cent slide in revenue to
ADollars 799.4m from ADollars 956.5m. The interim dividend has been cut to 6
cents a share from 13 cents.
In line with revised accounting standards, Western Mining directors have
reviewed the value of all non-current assets. They represent the second
leading Australian board to do so in as many weeks, following the ADollars
558m write-down by CSR, the sugar and building products group.
'Directors have adopted a conservative attitude in reducing the value of
mining properties, primarily gold operations, by ADollars 180m pre-tax,' the
board said. 'In addition, directors have decided to add ADollars 20m pre-tax
to the existing provision for environmental rehabilitation.'
Even excluding the write-downs, which were treated as abnormal items,
Western Mining's earnings were well down in the half. Operating earnings
fell 34.3 per cent to ADollars 114.3m from ADollars 173.9m before a tax
credit of ADollars 24.7m compared with a ADollars 29.6m payment previously.
The fall was even bigger on an equity-accounted basis, with the group's
associates contributing a ADollars 18.4m deficit against a ADollars 81.5m
premium. This produced a 57.4 per cent fall to ADollars 95.2m in equity
accounted net earnings from ADollars 223.4m.
The equity decline largely reflected a fall in contribution from the
company's 48.08 per cent-owned aluminium offshoot, Alcoa of Australia, to
ADollars 77.8m from ADollars 177.7m.
Gold was Western Mining's biggest profit earner in the half, with a ADollars
40.8m contribution, followed by ADollars 31.2m from oil and gas and ADollars
19.5m from nickel. Canadian operations lost ADollars 8.7m.
Directors said that although gold production fell 14.4 per cent in the half,
tonnage treated rose by 11.3 per cent, while unit costs rose 5.9 per cent.
Nickel prices fell by 17 per cent while exploration expenditure was cut from
ADollars 81.4m to ADollars 45.4m. Depreciation charges rose to ADollars
135.6m from ADollars 115.8m.
TNT, the diversified Australian transport group, has executed its
previously-announced flotation of stock in its US arm, TNT Freightways
Corporation, with a public offering on Nasdaq, the over-the-counter market.
The company is offering 12.5m shares in TNT Freightways at USDollars 19.50
each. Directors said the issue, with dividends payable, would raise about
ADollars 400m and TNT would retain a 20 per cent to 25 per cent interest in
the offshoot on completion.
</TEXT>
