<HEADLINE>
FT  14 FEB 92 / International Company News: Colgate to pay Dollars 670m for
US toiletries manufacturer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
COLGATE-PALMOLIVE, the large US household products company, is to buy Mennen
Company, a privately-owned personal care products manufacturer, for around
Dollars 670m.
News of the deal came as Colgate unveiled after-tax profits of Dollars
124.9m for the year. This compares with Dollars 321m in 1990, but the 1991
total was struck after a Dollars 243m restructuring charge in the third
quarter.
Mennen is based in New Jersey and involved in the US deodorant and
anti-perspirant market, where its sells under the Mennen Speed Stick, Mennen
Lady Speedstick and Mennen Teen Spirit brand names. It also makes baby
products - under the Baby Magic name - and men's toiletries.
In addition, the company sells in the Latin American and European markets,
and its total annual turnover is said to be in excess of Dollars 550m. No
profit figures were disclosed.
Colgate, which maintains that the Mennen product lines should complete its
personal care products - which range from toothpaste to soaps - will meet
around 80 per cent of the purchase price in stock and the remainder in cash.
In the final quarter of 1991, Colgate saw sales rise from Dollars 1.48bn to
Dollars 1.57bn, with after-tax earnings advancing from Dollars 73.5m to
Dollars 86.9m.
Colgate said Mennen's share of the US deodorant market was about 16 per
cent, making it a market leader. Of the total Dollars 550m-plus sales,
around Dollars 275m derived from the US.
However, the purchaser stressed that it was Mennen's exposure to less
developed markets outside the US, particularly in Latin America, that made
it especially attractive.
For the year overall, Colgate sales rose from Dollars 5.69bn to Dollars
6.06bn, with annual volume growth reaching 5 per cent. The company said
that, with the third-quarter restructuring charge omitted, profits showed a
15 per cent increase. Colgate shares rose Dollars  5/8 to Dollars 48.
</TEXT>
