FT  14 FEB 92 / Fujisankei may sell Virgin Music stake
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FUJISANKEI Communications, the Tokyo media group which holds 25 per cent of
Mr Richard Branson's Virgin Music Group, is likely to sell its stake if
negotiations to bring in a new majority shareholder for the business are
successful.
Discussions, which could be concluded by the end of the month, are
continuing with German media group Bertelsmann and UK-based electrical and
entertainment group Thorn EMI. A third US-based company is understood to
have entered the bidding in the past week.
Mr Branson is attempting to negotiate a joint venture or phased reduction of
his stake. He is keen to retain some investment for what one observer of the
deal described as 'sentimental reasons' - he created the division 20 years
ago, and built his airline and retailing empire around it.
Fujisankei, which paid Dollars 150m (Pounds 96m) in 1989 for its 25 per cent
stake, is not a bidder for the music division. Prices under discussion -
understood to be more than Dollars 1bn - would represent a considerable
profit over the Japanese group's initial investment.
The division's turnover has risen in that period - to around Pounds 350m -
and so have valuations of cashflow from libraries of copyrights.
The division is the world's largest remaining independent label, but it has
lacked manufacturing or distribution, which the interested bidders could
contribute.
Fujisankei is believed to be reluctant to remain a minority partner if a new
company takes majority control.
Last night Fujisankei was unavailable for comment.
My office, Page 10
