<HEADLINE>
FT  14 FEB 92 / Days lost by strikes in 1991 lowest on record
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEWER DAYS were lost through strikes last year than in any year since
records began 100 years ago, according to figures published yesterday by the
Department of Employment.
Provisional estimates put the loss at 800,000 days - the first time the
figure has fallen below 1m since 1940 - compared with annual averages of
12.9m days in the 1970s and 7.2m days for the 1980s.
The government is likely to use the figures during the election campaign as
evidence of the effectiveness of its reform of union law and to support its
claim that Labour would be unable to control the unions.
In 1991, 177,000 workers were involved in a total of 354 stoppages compared
with 298,000 engaged in 630 disputes in 1990.
The provisional figure for stoppages in December, the latest monthly figure
available, was 25 - the lowest for that month since 1932, when there were 21
stoppages.
INVESTMENT by manufacturing industries in capital goods fell by 15 per cent
last year compared with 1990, the Central Statistical Office said yesterday.
Spending on vehicles suffered the biggest decline, down by 39 per cent from
the previous year. Spending on plant and machinery fell 15 per cent and
investment on new buildings fell 9 per cent.
In the last quarter of last year capital expenditure was down 0.6 per cent
compared with the previous three-month period.
the value of investment in the fourth quarter of last year was Pounds 2.54bn
at seasonally adjusted 1985 prices, compared with Pounds 2.96bn in the
fourth quarter of 1990. Total capital expenditure last year was Pounds
10.27bn, compared with Pounds 12.14bn in 1990.
