<HEADLINE>
FT  14 FEB 92 / Election delays consumer spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALMOST one in 10 consumers are delaying making significant purchases because
of uncertainty about the general election, according to a survey published
by Barclaycard yesterday, Philip Coggan writes.
The proportion of those intending to postpone decisions such as moving
house, buying furniture or booking holidays, rises to 12 per cent among
people aged 35 to 64.
Barclaycard gives no explanation for this reluctance to spend, but it does
not appear to be related to Labour's plans to increase taxes on the higher
paid. Those in social classes AB are less likely to delay decisions than the
rest of the population.
The survey also shows that in spite of a rise in the official savings ratio,
the number of people who say they are saving has fallen to 33 per cent from
36 per cent in October 1991. At the same time, 18 per cent of those surveyed
were still running into debt, or using up savings.
The survey finds no sign of a revival in the housing market, with only 4 per
cent of those questioned planning to take out a mortgage in the next six
months.
Gallup interviewed 1,000 consumers on behalf of Barclaycard on January 28
and 29.
</TEXT>
