FT  14 FEB 92 / Police give pledge to businesses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN Stevens, the chief constable of Northumbria, has pledged that
tackling the effects of crime on local businesses will be a priority in his
force's use of its Urban Crime Fund money.
The force has the country's highest crime rate per 1,000 population and per
police officer. Under the new Urban Crime Fund initiative launched by the
Home Office for additional policing measures, Northumbria, Merseyside and
West Yorkshire forces have each been allocated Pounds 3.6m for 1992-93. The
Northumbria Police Authority is also contributing Pounds 1.2m to the force.
Proposals being submitted today to the Home Office, detailing how it plans
to use its allocation, include closed-circuit television networks on
industrial estates and in urban centres.
Mr Stevens said earlier this week that he had been told by local
industrialists that 'the only blight to this area is crime'.
