<HEADLINE>
FT  13 FEB 92 / International Company News: Sears, Roebuck cuts 600 retail
managerial jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARBARA DURR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SEARS, Roebuck, the large US retail and financial services company, has
announced a reorganisation of its retail group's field management structure.
The move will eliminate 600 jobs and bring cost savings of about Dollars 50m
by next year.
Sears said it would close 10 regional offices and 26 of its 72 district
merchandising units by mid-April. Responsibilities at the remaining
districts will be broadened.
The move comes just over a month after the company said it would cut 7,000
retail jobs to save it Dollars 50m this year.
In addition to reducing the workforce, Sears said yesterday it would lower
its compensation rates for sales personnel who sold on commission. This
would bring them more in line with the competition and change the company's
policies on such costly matters as overtime.
Mr Edward Brennan, chairman, said that while cost-saving programmes to date
had improved the bottom line by reducing the ratio of selling, general and
administrative expenses to revenues, 'we need to do much more to be
successful in this highly competitive environment'.
Sears said it was studying its retail headquarters staff and field staff
offices to see how to reorganise their structures.
</TEXT>
