<HEADLINE>
FT  13 FEB 92 / International Company News: CBS shows deficit of Dollars
85.8m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CBS, the US media group, yesterday posted a net loss of Dollars 85.8m, or
Dollars 5.32 a share, reflecting an after-tax loss of Dollars 195.5m, or
Dollars 12.06, from its baseball and football television coverage.
In 1990, CBS had net earnings of Dollars 110.8m, or Dollars 4.30 a share,
including an after-tax loss of Dollars 171.2m, or Dollars 6.65, on its
sports contracts. Sales in the year fell 7 per cent to Dollars 3.04bn from
Dollars 3.26bn.
Earnings in 1991 were further depressed by what Mr Laurence Tisch, chairman
and chief executive, called a 'stubborn' recession, expanding cable
competition and rising programming costs.
For the fourth quarter, the company had net income of Dollars 9.4m, or 61
cents a share, on sales of Dollars 937.4m, against a loss of Dollars 156m,
or Dollars 6.06, on sales of Dollars 919.7m.
The company had fourth-quarter operating earnings of Dollars 9.4m against an
operating loss of Dollars 175.3m a year earlier. For the full year, CBS's
loss from continuing operations was Dollars 98.7m against profits of Dollars
91.5m.
CBS, which paid Dollars 1.06bn for its four year baseball contracts has had
pre-tax losses of Dollars 604m for its sports coverage. CBS said these
contracts have been reduced to net realisation value and no further
write-offs are expected.
Mr David Londoner, an analyst at Wertheim Schroder, said the results roughly
met his expectations. 'I'm happy the third-quarter charge is done with. CBS
has good ratings now and 1992 is starting to look better.' Mr Londoner
expects CBS to earn Dollars 9-a-share in 1992.
Mr Tisch said he expected the company to return to profitability in 1992 in
spite of reduced advertiser demand for broadcast commercial time in the
first quarter of 1992.
