<HEADLINE>
FT  13 FEB 92 / International Company News: Mercedes considers cutting
20,000 jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MERCEDES-BENZ, the automotive unit of industrial group Daimler-Benz AG, is
considering cutting up to 20,000 jobs by 1995 as part of a radical
cost-cutting plan, industry sources said.
Sources said the management board had not yet decided how and when cuts of
this magnitude should occur, but a drastic reduction of Mercedes' worldwide
workforce of 238,000 people was necessary to achieve targetted savings of
DM4bn (Dollars 2.5bn) annually by 1995. Reuter reports.
Mercedes said last week a slowing down of car sales in Germany, coupled with
weak sales in other European markets and the recession in the US, could lead
to lay-offs.
The company would only confirm it was 'considering a reduction in the
workforce of several thousand.'
A cut of 20,000 jobs would mainly affect production workers in Germany as
the company strives to make its production process leaner, the sources said.
In addition to the 20,000 job cuts, another 3,000 jobs will be lost by 1995
from the administrative HQ of Mercedes and the Daimler holding in the
Stuttgart area.
A reduction in the administrative staff was announced by the Daimler
management board last year.
Last week, BMW announced it would axe 3,000 jobs by the end of this year to
increase productivity in light of sharper competition coupled with a
contraction of the German market.
</TEXT>
