<HEADLINE>
FT  13 FEB 92 / International Company News: Puma climbs back into profit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW FISHER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PUMA, the German sports shoe and equipment company owned by Aritmos of
Sweden, has finally broken into profit. Its return to the black for 1991
follows several difficult years of stiff competition in the US market and
production hold-ups in Asia.
The company made a group profit of around DM11m (Dollars 7m) before tax and
restructuring costs. Mr Stefan Jacobsson, chief executive, said the move out
of 1990's loss of DM9.4m made it clear the group was now on an upward trend.
Puma had already foreshadowed a return to profit, despite having hopes of an
end to its Far Eastern losses dashed by regional troubles in 1991. These
stemmed from the organisational difficulties of shifting production to
low-cost Indonesia, and a fire in the Philippines factory.
Formerly owned by members of the Dassler family, Puma slipped into loss in
1986, the year its preference shares were sold to the public.
</TEXT>
