<HEADLINE>
FT  13 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Rational debate succumbs to party
line - Political Notebook
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FIRST casualty of elections is rational debate. Between now and April 9
ministers and their shadows have a single priority: they must stick to what
the respective party leaderships decree is the 'line'.
The political imperative is that all the prominent figures speak with
precisely the same voice.
The content of their pronouncements becomes of secondary significance. There
must be no splits, wobbles or divisions. For the next eight weeks party
strategists and journalists will do little but scan every spoken and written
word for such gaffes.
Labour is most obviously vulnerable. The Conservative assault on its tax and
spending policies took off because some of Mr John Smith's colleagues were
heard playing slightly different tunes to those of the shadow chancellor.
Mr Smith would prefer a Trappist silence - at least until after the Budget
on March 10. His strategy has not won universal approval in the shadow
cabinet. In any event neither he nor his colleagues can escape the
questioning of the media.
Inevitably, variations show up in the textual analysis. This was underlined
again this week by Mr Roy Hattersley's comments on the top rate of tax.
Differences of emphasis become behind-the-scenes rows and personality
clashes. Party strategists argue for more rehearsals. Mr Smith is under
pressure to simplify Labour's tax and spending pledges and re-issue them on
a single sheet of paper.
Discussion on the Labour front bench about possible changes to the way
public borrowing is treated in the national accounts has been similarly
troublesome.
There is a perfectly good argument for adjustments to the present
conventions. No private company could treat the receipts from asset sales as
negative current spending, as the government does.
But senior Labour strategists have decided that however coherent the case
for change, it is better to try to suppress the debate. They find it too
easy to see the headlines: 'Labour plans to fiddle the books.'
The Conservatives have proved more adept at keeping to one line. The daily
co-ordination exercise between the five ministerial musketeers led by Mr
Richard Ryder is repaying its initial investment. Ministers anyway are more
practised than their shadows. The day-to-day business of government
inculcates the habit of sticking to the line.
But the musketeers have decided that there are some debates in which they
must not engage.
Scotland provides the most obvious example. In private, ministers readily
confess that the upsurge of nationalist sentiment north of the border may
require a radically different approach after the election.
But that must not even be hinted at in public before polling day.
Until then the line must be that the only choice is between independence and
the Union. That way the Scottish National party may take votes from Labour
and in the process save some of the remaining Conservative seats.
Mr John Major has not been immune from the pressures which have boxed in Mr
Neil Kinnock over taxation. He has been obliged to give unequivocal
commitments - not to increase value added tax, not to abolish the ceiling on
National Insurance contributions - which foreclose perfectly rational
options.
Tacit collusion has so far allowed the two main parties to avoid the same
trap on the environment. Neither seem ready to make it an election issue.
Only the Liberal Democrats are willing to discuss the sharp increase in the
price of fossil fuels which every politician with an interest in the subject
regards as inevitable. As one minister puts it: 'We all know that in the end
we will have to introduce some form of carbon tax. But for God's sake don't
quote me.'
It is not hard to imagine that the question will be put directly to Mr Major
and Mr Kinnock over the next few weeks; or that both will answer that they
would not dream of increasing domestic heating bills or, like the Liberal
Democrats, putting 50p on the price of a gallon of petrol.
So who loses from this widening gap between private reality and public
pledges? In the first instance it is the voter, who is denied the rational
debate. But perhaps the bigger loser is the winner of the election. Mr Major
and Mr Kinnock are busy making their own straitjackets.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
