<HEADLINE>
FT  13 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Business confidence is key to
lending, MPs told - Banking
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WEAK business confidence and hesitant bank managers bruised by bad debts
since the 1980s boom years may be the chief obstacles to lending to small
business when the economy recovers, a Commons committee heard yesterday.
Mr Brian Pearce, chief executive of Midland Bank, told the Treasury and
Civil Service committee that he believed the main UK banks would have plenty
of capital to expand their lending. Senior executives of the three other
leading banks appearing before the committee agreed.
Mr Martin Gray, chief executive of retail banking at National Westminster,
said: 'We are not seeing a plethora of excellent quality propositions which
we are having to turn away.'
Mr Pearce disclosed that Midland made provisions in the financial year just
ended against lending to 12,000 personal and small-business customers with
shortfalls in their debt repayments of between Pounds 15,000 and Pounds
250,000.
All the bankers present rejected suggestions that bank managers had less
power to make loan decisions than previously. Mr Geoffrey Miller, Barclays
managing director, said his managers had power to lend a minimum of Pounds
20,000 unsecured and Pounds 80,000 secured, rising in some large branches to
Pounds 1m. The other banks produced similar figures.
Mr Miller said 80 per cent of Barclays' lending decisions were taken at
branch level. Only 4,500 cases were referred to head office and 55,000 to
its 24 regional offices.
Asked what it was doing to help the Citizens' Advice Bureaux and other
counselling bodies deal with debt problems, Barclays said it had supplied
six managers to the CAB organisation. The committee suggested that some
managers who might otherwise be made redundant could be seconded to advice
organisations.
Mr Trevor Blackley, NatWest's general manager of UK branch banking business,
said his bank had given Pounds 250,000 over three years for money advice
bureaux.
All the banks said a statutory levy towards the costs of money advice would
not be appropriate. Mr David Pirrie, a director at Lloyds, said banks
already provided a great deal of financial counselling through their
branches.
MPs asked about mechanisms to ensure that the new banking code was enforced
after it came into force on March 16. They were told that the banking and
building society ombudsmen would collect details of infringements. Those
banks and building societies which persistently failed to observe its
provisions could be reported to the Bank of England or the Building
Societies Commission.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
