<PROFILE>_AN-CBMA5AEOFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920213
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  13 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Position of Labour's Scots MPs
questioned - Devolution
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A PASSING remark by Mr Robin Cook has once again raised the political
quandary posed by Scottish MPs being able to vote in Westminster on English
and Welsh issues.
Mr Ian Lang, the Scottish secretary, has written to Mr Neil Kinnock, the
Labour leader, asking whether 'the Cook doctrine' would inevitably apply to
other opposition frontbenchers.
The question resurfaced in a BBC Scotland programme on Friday when Mr Cook
apparently ruled out continuing as health secretary once the Scottish
parliament, pledged by Labour, was set up.
Last night Mr Kinnock's office tried to defuse the issue with a statement
stressing that the constitutional position would allow him to continue to
choose his cabinet from among all elected MPs once a Scottish assembly was
set up.
Mr Cook's remarks were said by colleagues to reflect a personal rather than
a party position. The Conservatives, however, indicated that they would
continue to press Mr Kinnock on the issue - dubbed the 'West Lothian
question' after it was raised by Mr Tam Dalyell, then MP for the now
disbanded constituency.
In his open letter to Mr Kinnock Mr Lang claims other Labour MPs who would
be affected include Mr Gordon Brown, trade and industry spokesman, about
five mid-ranking frontbenchers and Mr John Smith, shadow chancellor. Each of
these, he argues, would be wielding powers in England on aspects of
government business that Labour intends to devolve to the Scottish
parliament.
Mr Lang goes on to ask whether Labour's Scottish MPs would be excluded from
all main departments of state or whether they would be allowed to hold only
all-UK portfolios such as foreign affairs, defence and energy. 'If the
latter, does not this limit the prospects of your English and Welsh
colleagues occupying such posts,' asks Mr Lang.
At the weekend Mr Bryan Gould, Labour's environment spokesman, partially
tackled the question by hinting that the creation of English regional
assemblies would help resolve the problem.
</TEXT>
