<HEADLINE>
FT  13 FEB 92 / Battling the repossession scourge: Help for mortgage debtors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN and DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Council of Mortgage Lenders will today announce the number of homes
repossessed in the second half of last year. The figure will take the total
for 1991 up to just under 80,000 - a staggering increase on the 5,000
repossessed annually as recently as 10 years ago.
Yet the announcement is likely to be greeted with relief by the government
and the lenders. This is because it is far short of gloomier predictions
from housing analysts and campaigners that repossessions would top 100,000
last year.
Ministers are also optimistic that the chancellor's mortgage rescue package,
announced on December 19, will make a significant impact on the number of
repossessions in 1992.
The government's contribution to that package was an agreement to pay the
mortgage interest element of social security benefits direct to lenders, so
that it was not spent on other things.
In return, the lenders agreed not to repossess the homes of people covered
by such benefits. They also set aside up to Pounds 1bn for mortgage-to-rent
schemes under which housing associations would buy the homes of repossessed
borrowers and rent them back to their former owners.
The lenders claimed that the package would cut repossessions by 40,000 in
1992 - half of which would be through mortgage-to-rent schemes.
Yet almost two months after the chancellor announced his package, only three
building societies have announced details of their schemes - two of them
only pilot schemes covering fewer than 500 homes.
At the heart of the delay has been a clash of interests between the lenders
and the housing associations over the terms for mortgage-to-rent schemes.
The housing associations are keen to help keep borrowers in their homes but
are unwilling to take on an open-ended liability to bail out the lenders. So
they want the lenders to pay for outstanding repairs before handing over
homes, to write off arrears owed by borrowers and to cover their set-up and
administration costs.
They have also been unhappy about the terms on offer for loans to buy the
repossessed homes. The lenders were prepared to offer loans at 6 per cent to
8 per cent, but the associations reckoned that they needed interest rates of
below 5 per cent if they were to charge affordable rents.
Little progress was made in the negotiations between the lenders and the
housing associations until three weeks ago, when the Nationwide Building
Society launched its pilot mortgage-to-rent scheme. Anxious to be the first
to announce a scheme, Nationwide conceded most of the associations' demands.
Housing association costs were to be fully covered, mortgage arrears would
be written off and houses put into good repair before sale. Nationwide also
conceded interest rates for loans to the associations of between 3.5 per
cent and 5 per cent, in return for a share in any increase in value of the
houses.
Nationwide's terms were not widely welcomed by other lenders, who saw them
as overly generous. But they set a benchmark from which the housing
associations were reluctant to depart.
The Halifax pilot, announced on Friday, is thought to be broadly along the
same lines as Nationwide's. So too is the Bradford &amp; Bingley's, launched on
Monday.
Other initiatives are in the pipeline. Leeds Permanent will announce details
of its scheme today, with Woolwich following later this month. Some of the
mortgage indemnity insurers, who stand to lose as much as Pounds 3bn over
the next two years, are thought likely to set up their own schemes.
Most of the centralised lenders, the new mortgage companies which are among
the hardest hit by arrears and repossessions, have yet to devise rescue
schemes. The Mortgage Corporation, however, has set up a Pounds 15m business
expansion scheme to convert 150 homes into assured tenancies. It is also
talking to housing associations about renting empty properties to homeless
families.
The pace of setting up mortgage-to-rent schemes will now quicken. Many
involved in housing are, however, cautious about their ability to meet their
target. Sir George Young, the housing minister, last week declined to
endorse the 40,000 forecast, pointing out that it had been made by the
Council of Mortgage Lenders, not the government. Shelter, the pressure
group, earlier this week suggested that mortgage-rescue schemes would not
save more than 24,000 homes.
That pessimism is shared by Mr John Wriglesworth, housing market analyst at
the stockbrokers UBS Phillips &amp; Drew, who believes that rescue schemes will
have only a marginal effect on the level of repossessions. He is optimistic
about repossessions this year, however, because lenders are doing more to
help customers manage their finances.
'The building societies and other lenders have achieved a truly remarkable
reduction in the number of likely eviction cases. Around two thirds of their
serious arrears cases are now under control,' he says.
After the activity to set up mortgage rescue schemes the solution may have
lain with the lenders all along - in the form of better debt counselling.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
