<HEADLINE>
FT  13 FEB 92 / Early halt to CFC output is announced
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON, Science Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK will stop making ozone-destroying chemicals by the end of 1995, the
Department of the Environment and ICI, the country's largest chemical
manufacturer, said yesterday.
That will be two years ahead of the European Community deadline and five
years ahead of the internationally agreed Montreal Protocol.
The commitment matches the announcement by President Bush on Tuesday that
the US would stop producing chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs), the chemicals
causing most damage to the earth's protective ozone layer, by the end of
1995.
Both countries are accelerating the phase-out of CFCs in the light of new
evidence that the upper atmosphere is losing ozone far more rapidly than
scientists had realised previously. An 'ozone hole' may appear over densely
populated regions of the northern hemisphere, letting in harmful ultraviolet
radiation from the sun.
Greenpeace and Friends of the Earth, the environmental groups, said it was
not enough for the UK just to echo the new US timetable. Ms Tracy Heslop of
Greenpeace called for an immediate ban. 'All John Major has to do is pick up
the phone to ICI to stop the production of ozone destroyers,' she said.
Mr John Beckett, who is managing ICI's phase-out of CFCs, said an immediate
halt was not practical because many users, particularly in the refrigeration
industry, still had no available substitutes.
ICI halved CFC production from 80,000 tonnes in 1986 to 40,000 tonnes last
year, and the company has committed Pounds 200m to the development and
manufacturing of alternatives.
People are still not taking the CFC phase-out seriously enough, according to
Mr Beckett. 'We at ICI have had a free CFC recycling and recovery scheme for
some time and we're very disappointed at the response,' he said.
He added that ICI's new plant at Runcorn, Cheshire, which produces a
non-ozone-destroying substitute for CFC coolants, was running below full
capacity.
Yesterday Mr Klaus Toepfer, Germany's environment minister, urged the EC and
the US to help bring forward to 1995 the worldwide ban on ozone-destroying
chemicals.
Mr Toepfer said such a deadline should be set by a conference next November
in Copenhagen of 46 industrial and developing countries which are
signatories to the Montreal Protocol. He said he was in touch with his EC
and US counterparts about a joint push for a worldwide ban by 1995.
Mr Toepfer is also pressing German industry to stop making and using CFCs
next year. 'Germany will become the first CFC-free country in the world in
1993,' he said.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
