<HEADLINE>
FT  13 FEB 92 / Truck and van sales fall 17%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEW COMMERCIAL vehicle sales fell 17.2 per cent to 16,677 last month,
against 20,131 in January last year.
According to figures released by the Society of Motor Manufacturers and
Traders, the recession in the UK new-vehicle market shows no sign of easing,
with commercial-vehicle registrations in January 50 per cent down on the
same month three years ago.
Sir Hal Miller, SMMT chief executive, said sales last month were the lowest
January total since 1981 and reflected 'the continuing serious state of the
commercial-vehicle industry'.
Sales of light and medium trucks and medium vans were particularly hard hit.
Registrations of new trucks (above 3.5 tonnes gross vehicle weight) have
fallen by 63.9 per cent in the past three years from 6,442 in January 1989
to 2,325 last month.
Rover again lost ground in the small-van market, while sales of
Mercedes-Benz and Nissan medium vans fell sharply. Volkswagen improved in
this sector, helped by the progressive launch last year of its Transporter
range.
In the heavy-truck market (above 15 tonnes gross vehicle weight), Volvo
ousted Leyland DAF from sector leadership.
