<HEADLINE>
FT  13 FEB 92 / Property prospects worsen
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONFIDENCE in the recovery of the UK commercial property industry has
diminished during the past three months, according to a survey by Gallup,
the research group.
More than half the property companies and funds questioned did not expect an
upturn in the market for at least one to two years.
The survey found that 64 per cent of respondents believed conditions would
improve and 9 per cent believed they would worsen. Last October 75 per cent
of respondents thought conditions would improve and 3 per cent thought they
would worsen.
Most respondents expected the retail property market to recover first. The
market considered least likely to lead a recovery was business space for
light industrial and office use, closely followed by offices. The City of
London was the least popular area in the country with property investors.
British Land, the property company headed by Mr John Ritblat, was considered
by nearly a quarter of respondents to be the most successful property
company of 1991. Land Securities, the largest UK property company, was rated
the most successful by 5 per cent of respondents.
Gallup, which carried out the survey with Chartered Surveyors Weekly, an
industry magazine, interviewed 98 directors of large property companies and
funds which control Pounds 59bn of property.
CSW/Gallup Confidence Index. Chartered Surveyor Weekly, Builder House, 1
Millharbour, London E14 9RA. Pounds 49.95.
