<HEADLINE>
FT  13 FEB 92 / CBI reports poor prospects for manufacturing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROSPECTS for a recovery in UK manufacturing remain weak, with only two
regions expecting a 'slight' improvement in orders and output during the
next four months.
Only the north-west of England and the west Midlands - one of the regions
worst affected by the recession - expect a small rise in orders, while
manufacturing companies elsewhere expect production to remain flat or to
deteriorate.
The lastest findings of the Confederation of British Industry and Business
Strategies survey of regional industrial trends add to the bleak picture of
the UK economy painted by the Bank of England in its Quarterly Bulletin
earlier this week. The Bank admitted the economy was still in recession and
did not predict when an upturn would occur.
Although little change in output or demand was expected over the next four
months, the CBI survey points towards a reshuffle in the fortunes of the 11
regions.
Scotland, which has appeared to withstand the manufacturing recession
comparatively well, expects a sharper than average fall in orders and
output. The survey said Scotland was helped by the boom in North Sea safety
and technical work but now appeared to be slipping into a weaker position.
Scotland also recorded the biggest fall in optimism about prospects. Along
with the north of England, the south-east and the west Midlands, this severe
pessimism reflected the gloomy outlook for exports, the survey said. Overall
optimism, which rose marginally in the previous survey, declined.
The steepest fall in new orders in the past four months was in the west
Midlands, Scotland and Wales. Total orders fell in every region - a finding
at odds with expectations expressed in the last survey. The CBI said the
sharp fall in demand caught many companies by surprise, one reason being the
failure of export orders to live up to expectations.
One result of the recession has been a striking change in the distribution
of manufacturing activity. Before the recession, levels of capacity
utilisation were lowest in Scotland and the north. Now they enjoy the
highest rates while the south-east, Wales, East Anglia and the west Midlands
are more likely to have companies working below full capacity.
The survey predicted declines in investment in plant in all regions bar the
east Midlands, where little change was expected. All regions expressed
positive intentions to invest in training.
Economic viewpoint, Page 19
