<HEADLINE>
FT  13 FEB 92 / UK News (Employment): Rail sell-off campaign targets Tory
marginals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO RAIL unions yesterday entered the pre-election campaign with a warning
that rail privatisation could cut services to Tory-held marginal
constituencies.
The campaign, which will cost Pounds 70,000, urges voters in the 62 most
marginal Tory-held constituencies not to return candidates who support
privatisation. The initiative is part of the rail unions' Campaign for
Better Railways, which was launched two years ago.
It began yesterday with the distribution to all BR employees of a leaflet
setting out the unions' view of what privatisation will mean to them. The
unions will use posters, advertising and leaflets to drive their message
home to voters in the selected constituencies.
Mr Jimmy Knapp, general secretary of the RMT transport union, said the
Conservative party was planning to include rail privatisation in its
election manifesto. 'We know that the privatisation of British Rail will
result in the destruction of much of our rail network,' he said.
'There will be closures of lines, fewer trains, much higher fares and, when
the drive for profit takes over, safety margins will become depressed and
narrower.'
He said privatisation would push passengers away from trains and lead to
further congestion on roads. Privatisation threatened the jobs of a third of
RMT members, about 40,000 rail staff.
Mr Richard Rosser, general secretary of the TSSA white-collar rail union,
said: 'We know many passengers are saying 'anything is better than this'. We
will show them that things are as bad as they are now because BR is already
being forced to operate as a private company.'
He said a white paper detailing government plans had been expected by the
end of last year. 'So the first one to fail to achieve a Citizen's Charter
target is the prime minister himself.'
Mr Malcolm Rifkind, transport minister, yesterday said privatisation would
lead to an expansion of the railways. The white paper is expected this
month.
A confidential BR document leaked to the Labour party last month warned that
privatisation would mean the loss of InterCity links for dozens of towns and
cities in the UK, many in Conservative-held constituencies.
</TEXT>
