<DOCNO>FT921-9146</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CBMA5AEAFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920213
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  13 FEB 92 / Labour pledges to keep fraud case juries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A LABOUR government would not move to end trial by jury in fraud cases, Ms
Marjorie Mowlam, the Labour City affairs spokeswoman, said last night.
She said replacing juries with alternatives such as the three-person
tribunal advocated by the Roskill Fraud Trials Committee would risk
undermining 'basic civil rights'.
She said the party would, however, consider appointing specialist legal
advisers to juries in complex fraud cases.
Ms Mowlam said Labour would streamline the roles of the bodies responsible
for fighting fraud as part of a wide-ranging review of domestic approaches
to the pro-secution of such alleged crimes.
It would be given a broad remit, including consideration of the following
areas:
Improving the efficiency with which resources currently earmarked for
dealing with fraud are used. Ms Mowlam says there was duplication of effort
among the bodies with fraud-related responsibilities, including the Serious
Fraud Office, the Crown Prosecution Service, the Department of Trade and
Industry, the City's self-regulating organisations and the Stock Exchange.
Savings from better use of these resources could help the SFO to improve its
performance in prosecuting large fraud cases. Labour would retain the SFO
and the CPS as separate bodies.
Opening the way for the SFO and other prosecuting bodies to opt for civil
instead of criminal proceedings if there was a better chance of obtaining a
conviction.
Encouraging prosecuting counsel to limit the number of counts rather than
'throwing the book' at defendants. The SFO has been criticised for embarking
on all-embracing prosecutions that clog up the courts for months or even
years and become complex beyond the grasp even of experienced judges.
Placing time limits on both the duration of trials and delays in bringing
cases to court.
'Bringing successful prosecutions should act as a deterrent to others
considering fraud,' Ms Mowlam said. 'When the delay in bringing a case is
years, the deterrent effect is minimal.'
Examining the effectiveness of the pre-trial hearings introduced at the
recommendation of the Roskill committee.
Ms Mowlam also called on the government to use the lessons of the Guinness
proceedings as part of the basis for changing takeover legislation and
reforming auditing and accounting practices. Mr Peter Lilley, trade and
industry secretary, should 'turn his mind to improving the DTI's performance
as a regulator', she said.
Ivor Owen adds: Ms Mowlam later reinforced these criticisms in the Commons,
arguing that the need for action had been underlined by the collapse of the
third case concerning Guinness, and the 'potential collapse' of the second
Guinness case.
She went on to question whether fraud could be dealt with under the existing
law, and emphasised that the three people who had been convicted had spent
less time in jail than the time that was taken up by the trial.
Recalling that the sentence imposed on Mr Ernest Saunders, the former
Guinness chairman, had been reduced because of ill-health, she said he had
appeared on the media earlier yesterday 'in blooming health and protesting
his innocence'.
Mr John Redwood, corporate affairs minister, refused to comment on
individual cases but confirmed that Lord Mackay of Clashfern, the Lord
Chancellor, was reviewing court procedures.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
