<HEADLINE>
FT  13 FEB 92 / Island ferry link cleared by MMC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   THE OPERATORS of ferry services to the Isle of Wight
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
labelled the world's most expensive route by aggrieved islanders - were
yesterday cleared by the Monopolies and Mergers Commission of acting against
the public interest, Richard Tomkins writes.
The commission concluded after an eight-month study that Wightlink, the
biggest Isle of Wight ferry operator, enjoyed a technical monopoly on
services to and from the UK mainland, but cleared it of abusing its
position.
Isle of Wight County Council said it was disappointed. It had hoped that the
commission would force Wightlink to give up at least one of its three routes
to a competitor.
Wightlink, a subsidiary of the Bermuda-based Sea Containers, is the biggest
of four operators on Isle of Wight routes. The others are Red Funnel, a
subsidiary of Associated British Ports, and two independents: Hovertravel
and Cowes Express.
The MMC says Wightlink carries 71 per cent of ferry passengers, 85 per cent
of cars, 80 per cent of lorries and 94 per cent of coaches. Its profits are
put at about 12 per cent of the replacement costs of its assets.
Cross-Solent Ferries. Monopolies and Mergers Commission. Cmnd 1825. HMSO.
Pounds 13.55.
