<HEADLINE>
FT  13 FEB 92 / UK News (Employment): Unions face clash on recruits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LEADERS OF the FDA Civil Service union decided yesterday to reject the
advice of a Trades Union Congress disputes panel and accept health service
managers into membership for the first time.
The decision by the union's executive will cause friction with the Nalgo
public service union, whose members include some of the 200-plus general
managers who have applied for FDA membership.
Nalgo had asked the TUC disputes panel to instruct the FDA not to recruit
the managers, who are among a group of about 800.
The panel last week refused Nalgo's request but advised the FDA against
recruiting the managers, saying the introduction of another union into the
health service would not be helpful.
The dispute is politically sensitive because the government has said it
plans to legislate to weaken the TUC's adjudication role in settling union
membership disputes by giving individuals greater freedom to join the union
of their choice.
Ms Liz Symons, FDA general secretary, said yesterday that most of the health
service managers who had applied for union membership were not in any union
at all.
'They are attracted by our service for people on personal contracts. We
believe they should have the opportunity to belong to a trade union. Most
are not in one.'
The FDA will, however, face strong opposition from Nalgo when it attempts to
take into membership those people already in the public service union.
Mr Keith Sonnet, Nalgo assistant general secretary, said his union would
look at individual cases but 'we would not want to see our members join
another union'.
Under TUC rules the FDA would have to seek Nalgo's approval before
recruiting its members. The disputes panel said that it saw no reason why
Nalgo or any other unions should 'facilitate transfers at the insistence of
the FDA'.
Public rows about the transfers would inevitably attract the attention of Mr
Michael Howard, employment secretary, who argues that unions should not
refuse membership to an individual because of objections from another union.
</TEXT>
