<HEADLINE>
FT  13 FEB 92 / Clinton deeper in draft-dodge controversy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNOR Bill Clinton of Arkansas suffered a fresh blow to his presidential
campaign yesterday when he was forced to release a letter casting doubt on
denials of draft-dodging during the Vietnam war.
The release of the letter pre-empted a disclosure on national television,
but the timing could not be worse with less than a week remaining until the
critical New Hampshire Democratic primary election next Tuesday.
Senator Tom Harkin of Iowa, who is challenging Mr Clinton for the Democratic
nomination, said: 'I think voters should be concerned about his veracity and
character.'
The letter, which was leaked to ABC News from Pentagon files, concerns Mr
Clinton's intention to serve in the reserve officers' training corps (ROTC)
at the University of Arkansas. This was a move that allowed him to avoid
military service in Vietnam for four years. However, he went to Oxford as a
Rhodes scholar and never made good on the pledge.
The letter, written in 1969, expresses regret for misleading an Arkansas
reserve officer by failing to disclose the depth of his opposition to the
war. He also thanks the officer for 'saving me from the draft'.
After the original charges of draft-dodging surfaced, Mr Clinton denounced
the story as Republican muck-raking. He also denied he was a draft-dodger,
noting that in the autumn of 1969 he had made himself eligible for the
draft. (He received a high number in the lottery and was therefore not
called to serve).
The letter gives a poignant account of how Mr Clinton wrestled with his
conscience. The young student condemns the Vietnam war and the draft, but
says he did not wish to be a draft-resister. The ROTC seemed a compromise.
But having received the deferment, Mr Clinton said he was consumed by
anguish and the loss of self-regard. 'I decided to accept the draft, in
spite of my beliefs, for one reason: to maintain my political viability
within the system.'
He hints at his future career in national politics. 'For years I have worked
to prepare myself for a political life characterised by both practical
political ability and concern for rapid social progress.'
By releasing the letter, Mr Clinton has avoided charges of a 'cover-up' but
runs the risk of having his economic and social programme - which attracted
much support in the initial phase of the Democratic campaign - subsumed by
the controversy over his Vietnam years.
Vice-President Dan Quayle was dogged by similar controversy in the 1988
presidential campaign, although unlike Mr Clinton he did not put himself
forward for the draft and served instead in the Indiana National Guard.
</TEXT>
