<HEADLINE>
FT  13 FEB 92 / Libyan gesture to Paris on bombings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE LIBYAN government has agreed to co-operate with France in an
investigation of the 1989 terrorist attack on a UTA jet liner over West
Africa but has again refused to extradite two Libyan agents accused of
plotting the Lockerbie disaster nine months earlier.
The Libyan authorities' stance was reported to the United Nations by Mr
Boutros Boutros-Ghali, the UN secretary general. He pressed Libya on the
matter after a Security Council resolution last month that in effect called
for the handing over of the Lockerbie bombers to British or US justice.
The secretary general said Colonel Muammer Gadaffi, the Libyan leader, had
informed his special envoy that a judge was already appointed to try the
accused. If Britain and the US were dissatisfied with the Libyan judges they
should send judicial observers, Col Gadaffi advised.
In his report to the Security Council, the secretary general said he
subsequently got further clarification of the Libyan position in both the
UTA and Pan Am disasters, which took a total of 441 lives.
Libya now accepted French requests for all material evidence and access to
documents, as well as the assembling of witnesses, and the facilities for
contacts and meetings to investigate the UTA disaster.
This decision was taken because France - which did not seek extradition of
the suspected terrorists - acted 'in conformity with international law and
did not infringe upon the sovereignty of Libya,' according to Col Gadaffi.
The Libyan response came after reports that the suspects in the Pan Am
bombing had disappeared and might have been executed. However, this has been
denied and Mr Boutros-Ghali has made no mention of it.
Libya is expected now to invite a French magistrate to Tripoli to
investigate the downing of the French jet, rather than surrender four agents
France wants to question.
US State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said Libya was trying to
confuse the issue and 'remains unwilling to comply in any meaningful way'
with the UN resolution, Reuter reports from Washington.
'We fully expect Libya to comply with those demands. If Libya fails to
comply, as we've said before we consider all options open,' he said.
Libya, meanwhile, is preparing for a possible punitive western military
strike by hiding its mobile Soviet-made Scud missiles and strengthening its
air defences, a US official claimed.
'We've had considerable evidence that the Libyans are concerned about some
offensive military action,' said a government official, who added that the
Libyan actions had been evident for many weeks.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 4
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-9171</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CBMA5ADLFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920213
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  13 FEB 92 / Cresson wins the round but party is reeling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN DAVIDSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AS expected, France's conservative opposition parties failed in their
attempt this week to bring down the Socialist government of Mrs Edith
Cresson, when their censure motion on its handling of the George Habash
scandal fell far short of the required parliamentary majority.
But Mrs Cresson's government cannot easily shrug off the political damage
caused by the controversy over the ostensibly unauthorised hospitalisation
in Paris of the Palestinian leader. The affair has undoubtedly added to the
popular discontent with the administration of President Francois Mitterrand.
Winding up the debate with a combative defence of the government's record,
Mrs Cresson called on her Socialist supporters to mobilise 'for the next 400
days', to be ready for the general elections scheduled for the spring of
next year. It was a forceful performance, but the critical date for Mrs
Cresson's government is not 400 days away, but less than 40, in the local
and regional elections of March 22.
At the best of times, the Socialists would expect to be handicapped in these
elections, weighted in favour of the rural vote and conservative local
forces.
But to judge from recent opinion polls, that verdict is likely to be severe.
The Socialists' share of the vote may slide to below an average of 20 per
cent.
If that happens, they could no longer claim to be the largest single party
in France. The pressure on President Mitterrand to replace Mrs Cresson with,
say, Mr Jacques Delors, the European Commission president, might then become
intense. It might become hard to resist pressure for early general
elections.
Socialist support in the Rhone-Alpes region, according to a survey by the
BVA polling institute, is likely to fall to 18 per cent, 10 percentage
points less than in the previous regional elections of 1986. In the Auvergne
region, the Socialist vote could drop from 30.8 per cent to 19.5 per cent.
In the Ile de France region round Paris, the Socialist vote would drop even
further, to 16 per cent, compared with 28.6 per cent in 1986.
These losses would not be reflected in a corresponding swing to the
traditional conservative parties. In all three these regions, the Gaullists
and the centre-right UDF are together likely to lose voting share: in the
Rhone-Alpes it would drop from 41.9 per cent to 39 per cent, in Auvergne
from 46.5 to 42 per cent. The big gains, according to the polls, would be
made by the protest-vote parties: the extreme right-wing National Front and
the ecological movements.
</TEXT>
