<HEADLINE>
FT  13 FEB 92 / Tories unite with Labour to attack EC budget plan: Hurd says
Delors is bidding for a larger rise than is justified
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STRASBOURG, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Conservative and Labour parties were yesterday united in their criticism
of European Commission plans to raise European Community budget revenue by a
third over the next five years.
The determined opposition in Westminster arose even though Mr Jacques
Delors, the Commission president, said the plan was 'the minimum necessary'
to make a success of the Maastricht treaty on political and monetary union.
Mr Delors made a strenuous effort to head off a row over the UK's rebate on
its budget payments, and to pre-empt criticism of Commission plans to help
industry restructure.
But in London, Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, said he did not believe
there was a case for raising the resources' ceiling available to the EC over
the next five years, because there was room for growth within the existing
ceiling.
'Mr Delors is bidding for more than is justified. We will go into a whole
range of Community meetings lasting several months, and at the end of the
day all of this has to be agreed by all of us,' he said on BBC radio.
For Labour, Mr Chris Smith, an opposition Treasury spokesman, said reform of
the Common Agricultural Policy would he negotiations, and he emphasised the
need for reform of the regional and structural funds, to benefit British
regions.
Brussels wants the budget to rise from Ecu66.6bn (Pounds 47.4bn) this year
to Ecu87.5bn (at 1992 prices) in 1997 to accommodate greater spending on
regional aid, foreign policy, farm reform and a strengthened research effort
to sharpen industrial competitiveness.
Mr Delors, presenting the 1993-97 plan to the European Parliament, recalled
that the first five year plan, agreed in 1988, had made possible the
achievements of the single market, more even EC development through regional
spending, and financial stability. At least equal effort was now needed for
European union to succeed, he said. 'We must implement the agreement of
Maastricht.'
Anticipating resistance to the size of the increase, Mr Delors pointedly
reminded the 12 heads of government that 'half of the rise comes about
because of political commitments you undertook, and the other half you would
have to spend anyway' if the EC did not exist.
At Maastricht in December, the 12 agreed to increase substantially fiscal
transfers to the four poorest member states - Spain, Ireland, Portugal and
Greece. This accounts for half the proposed Ecu21bn increase.
The other three priorities share the rest, but if member states were acting
individually, the cost of helping eastern Europe, agriculture and industrial
restructuring 'would still have to be met', Mr Delors argued.
Downing Street officials yesterday stressed, however, that although Mr John
Major, the prime minister, had agreed at the Maastricht summit to the
cohesion fund to help poorer EC countries, he had not signed up to spending
on this scale.
The UK is a net contributor to the budget despite the 1985 rebate
arrangement which Germany - by far the biggest net contributor - is now
questioning.
Mr Delors confirmed that the UK rebate would not be re-examined until after
the British general election, due at the latest by July. 'The Commission
does not intend to upset that (election) process through its proposals.'
UK officials stressed that any change in the rebate arrangement would
require the unanimity of the 12, so that Britain could veto it.
Mr Delors strongly defended his controversial industrial restructuring
plans, vehemently insisting that 'we are not talking about French
interventionism'.
There would be 'equality of access' to the new 'bottom-up' attempt to make
research more responsive to industrial innovation, and an independent
scientific committee would decide where the EC should spend
'competitiveness' funds which would rise to Ecu3.5bn in 1997 at today's
prices.
