<HEADLINE>
FT  13 FEB 92 / International Company News: Scitex shrugs off difficulties
with 31% improvement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SCITEX, the Israeli maker of electronic pre-press systems, yesterday
reported a 31 per cent increase in net profits in 1991 to Dollars 100.6m,
dodging both the worst effects of recession in the US and Europe, its main
markets, and the collapse of the Robert Maxwell empire with which it was
associated.
The profit rise was much less spectacular than the more than 100 per cent
increase of the two previous years, but Scitex executives were far from
disappointed, given the circumstances.
Mr Maxwell was chairman and controlled 15 per cent of Scitex until little
more than a month before his death when he sold out. It subsequently emerged
the shares were owned by Maxwell pension funds, not the private Robert
Maxwell Group as previously thought, but proceeds from the sale worth Pounds
107m (Dollars 192.6m) had gone to the Robert Maxwell Group instead of the
pension funds.
'He never had much impact on the running of our business, even as chairman,'
Mr Giora Bitan, Scitex's chief financial officer, said yesterday.
'But to have had a substantial portion of our shares in the hands of the
Maxwell receivers is not something we would have liked.'
Mr Bitan said the quick productive returns Scitex equipment offered printers
and publishers had bolstered demand, despite the recession. Sales and
service revenue rose 22 per cent from Dollars 351.5m in 1990 to Dollars
430.2m in 1991.
He said the outlook for 1992 was 'not easy, and said the company was
increasingly targetting the growing 'mid-range' market where small print
houses were switching from black and white to colour reproduction.
Mr Bitan said this sector was aimed to grow from about 5 per cent of sales
last year to 15 per cent in 1993.
Scitex costs moved up last year to Dollars 165m from Dollars 135m in 1990.
Net R&amp;D expenses were Dollars 26.9m, compared with Dollars 22m. Earning per
share were Dollars 2.70 with a total dividend for the year of Dollars 0.40
per share.
</TEXT>
