<HEADLINE>
FT  13 FEB 92 / Reuters profits increase 6.3% in spite of fall in new orders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
REUTERS Holdings, the financial information and news company, reported a 6.3
per cent increase in annual pre-tax profits to Pounds 340.3m, in spite of
continuing weak conditions in its traditional markets.
The number of employees fell by 475 to 10,335 and the group incurred
rationalisation costs of Pounds 23.5m in Europe and North America. It also
warned that further cuts might be necessary this year.
Mr Peter Job, managing director, said Reuters had experienced a big fall in
new orders at the end of 1990, and had reacted by improving efficiency.
He added: 'In the near term, market recovery is not in sight and we expect
revenue growth to slow further in 1992, particularly since, in response to
our customers' needs, we have generally avoided increasing prices.'
Turnover rose 7.1 per cent to Pounds 1.47bn in the year to December 31,
while earnings per share increased 10.5 per cent to 54.7p (49.5p).
Strong cash flow increased net cash from Pounds 217.1m to Pounds 502.9m and
interest income rose from Pounds 30.4m to Pounds 49.6m.
Because of its strong balance sheet, Reuters increased the final dividend to
12.3p (10.6p), raising the total by 13.3 per cent to 17p. The dividend cover
falls from 3.29 to 3.21.
Reuters said the long-delayed second phase of Dealing 2000, its automated
trading system which enables foreign exchange traders to complete
transactions on-screen, had been successfully tested by 30 banks in London
and New York. The group plans a formal launch within weeks.
Reuters had also satisfactorily tested Globex, which will provide
screen-based trading of futures and options. Globex is being created jointly
by Reuters with the Chicago Board of Trade and the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange and is to be launched later this year.
Mr Job said Reuters had been under great pressure to provide more
information about the group, and for the first time had broken down
operating profits by geographical area, excluding the rationalisation
provisions and central costs of Pounds 113.8m.
It said Europe contributed Pounds 305m, compared with Pounds 312m in 1990;
Asia Pacific Pounds 124m, up from Pounds 110m; America a loss of Pounds 5m,
compared with a loss of Pounds 8m. Visnews, its television agency, made
Pounds 1m (Pounds 4m).
Reuters shortened the depreciation period for its subscriber terminals from
five to four years, at a cost of Pounds 29m.
Lex, Page 20
