<HEADLINE>
FT  13 FEB 92 / Arts: Laurie Booth - Queen Elizabeth Hall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLEMENT CRISP
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Laurie Booth's newest piece, Requiair, is subtitled 'A Flight Dance', and
Nigel Coates' design is of a pair of white aeroplane wings hanging above the
dance area. Hans Peter Kuhn's sound installation is an often ravishing
sequence of noises interspersed with bird-song, faint curlew pipings, and
what may well be the first electronic celestial choir. We seem to be poised
between earth and heavens, as if on top of a windy hill-top - the Elizabeth
Hall's hideous and steeply raked auditorium encourages this feeling -
looking at dance that meditates upon ideas of flight and the aspirations
behind those ideas.
It is thus I interpret Booth's work for himself and four colleagues: Jo
Chandler, Desiree Cherrington, Gary Lambert and Ellen van Schuylenburch,
which received its London premiere on Tuesday and Wednesday. The dancers
wear unisex shirts and trousers in anonymous clayey shades and, like the
clothes, Booth's dances - which had an erotically challenging tension in
recent duets with Russell Maliphant - here look neutral, almost neutered.
The text, as displayed by Booth himself, is fascinating, because his own
movement style - sinuous, coloured by stunningly effective accelerandos that
melt into quiescent poses - is so richly varied. The dancer and the dance
become one. His companions, able dancers all, can nowhere match (as Russell
Maliphant can match, and indeed challenge) the many nuances of Booth's
bravura language. It owes something to martial arts, to T'ai Chi, to contact
improvisation, Indian dance and capoeira - whence come the flicker-quick
gesture and the long, logical flow of action. It owes as much to Booth's own
prodigious concentration, which draws us into his imaginative world. In
Requiair, the ideas are oblique, allusive: the manner of post-modern dance
is never going to provide the obvious imagery of aerial ecstasy that ballet
can furnish. Instead, Booth appears like a Daedalus, dreaming of escape by
flight. In one of the most touching and beautiful sections of the piece -
which is uneven, but often rewarding - Booth lies on the ground as Kuhn's
shimmering sound-world hangs above him, and seems to meditate upon movement
that he then starts to explore. In contrast, he also creates a trio for the
two men and himself which is a dazzlingly accented scherzo of contact games,
of falls, holds, and wild clamberings.
The dance runs for about 70 minutes. I think it too long, and because of the
dissipation of movement ideas among the cast, too diffuse: few of its massed
effects touch the potency of Booth's own presence. But it is also a work
from a secure and eminently gifted creator, whose vision of dancing is
strong, highly personal, and always convincing. The performance initiated
the annual 'Spring Loaded' festival of new dance which now moves to The
Place: there will be further reports in due course.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 17
</PAGE>
