<HEADLINE>
FT  13 FEB 92 / Isle of Wight ferry operators cleared by MMC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   THE OPERATORS of ferry services to the Isle of Wight
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
labelled the world's most expensive route by aggrieved islanders - were
yesterday cleared by the Monopolies Commission of acting against the public
interest.
The commission concluded after an eight-month study that Wightlink, the
biggest Isle of Wight ferry operator, enjoyed a technical monopoly on
services to and from the UK mainland, but cleared it of abusing its
position.
Isle of Wight County Council said it was disappointed by the verdict. It had
hoped that the commission would force Wightlink to give up at least one of
its three routes to a competitor.
It took comfort from a decision by Mr Peter Lilley, the trade and industry
secretary, that the director general of fair trading should check the
position again in three years' time.
Wightlink, a subsidiary of Bermuda-based Sea Containers, is the biggest of
four operators on Isle of Wight routes. The others are Red Funnel, a
subsidiary of Associated British Ports, and two independents: Hovertravel
and Cowes Express.
The Monopolies Commission launched its investigation into the four
companies' ferry services last year because of complaints from islanders
about fares. It received almost 600 letters on the subject during its
inquiry.
In the absence of bridges, tunnels or regular air services between the
island and the mainland, the ferries offer the only means of crossing the
Solent to nearby Southampton, Portsmouth or Lymington.
Residents said high fares limited their ability to visit the mainland and
discouraged tourist traffic, on which the local economy was heavily
dependent.
The commission's report says Wightlink has a technical monopoly on the
island's ferry services, carrying 71 per cent of the passengers, 85 per cent
of cars, 80 per cent of lorries and 94 per cent of coaches.
The company's profits, it says, are substantial, at about 12 per cent of the
replacement costs of its assets. They are not so great, however, as to be
regarded as against the public interest and the other operators are making
losses or moderate profits.
The commission acknowledges that ferry fares per mile on Isle of Wight
services are among the highest in the UK. A day return for a car and family
of four can cost Pounds 59.40 on a summer weekend, it says.
The shortest crossing distance, Lymington to Yarmouth, is just under 4 miles
and the shortest crossing time, Southsea to Ryde, is 10 minutes.
The report says comparisons with other routes are of limited value, however.
Short crossings tend to have a higher cost per mile than long ones, it says.
Many comparable Scottish services are heavily subsidised and cross-Channel
ferries carry much heavier loadings.
Mr James Sherwood, president of Sea Containers, said the report vindicated
the company's strategy since acquiring the Isle of Wight ferry services from
British Rail in 1984.
'This strategy has been to increase capacity and frequency of sailings and
standards of on-board comfort while not increasing tariffs by more than
inflation,' he said.
Cross-Solent Ferries. Monopolies and Mergers Commission. Cmnd 1825. HMSO.
Pounds 13.55.
</TEXT>
