<HEADLINE>
FT  13 FEB 92 / CIS may founder over split-up of centralised armed forces:
Russia seems certain to set up its own army
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Commonwealth of Independent States, the successor to the Soviet Union,
may founder tomorrow in Minsk - where it began a little more than two months
ago. A formal announcement to that effect is unlikely: but another session
of papering over the cracks is probably impossible.
The root problem is army, the only surviving institution of the Soviet state
but one whose future is increasingly uncertain as the individual republics,
including Russia, opt for separate forces.
Fears over the army's reaction to its disintegration as a unified force
representing the CIS were highlighted yesterday when rumuors of a possible
coup attempt against President Yeltsin swept some western stock markets.
They emerged after Mr Eduard Shevardnadze, the former Soviet foreign
minister, said the economic crisis and tensions in the armed forces could
lead to a coup in Moscow.
Such tensions are likely to persist, in part because in the past week, a
succession of statements by the senior military advisors around the Russian
president, Mr Boris Yeltsin, made it clear that they expected the
announcement of the creation of separate Russian armed forces immediately
after the Minsk summit.
Yesterday officials in Moscow said the decree was likely to be promulgated
at the weekend - and that it would envisage an armed force totalling 1.5m
men, becoming a professional force in the course of the next few years.
In an interview with the Financial Times yesterday, Col Alexei Tsaryov,
chairman of the defence sub committee of the Russian parliament, said that a
resolution along these lines could be submitted to the parliament today
after authoritative opinion shifted during the past week in favour of a
Russian force.
He warned, however, that the move would run into severe opposition from the
armed forces general staff, headed by Marshal Yevgeny Shaposhnikov.
The general staff has prepared 14 documents calling for a unified command
for the Commonwealth armed forces, with provision for a council of defence
ministers to supervise it. A working group from the Commonwealth states has
over the past two days been discussing these documents in Minsk in
preparation for tomorrow's summit.
'Their conception is for practically unlimited power for the general staff.
There is no place in it for the parliaments of the states. This is
completely unacceptable to us, and it will be to other republics.
The defence committee will propose that the statement on Russian armed
forces should include the following:
Russia will create its own defence capability;
Other states should then decide what association they wish to have with the
Russian forces, especially with the nuclear forces which Russia plans to
monopolise
An interparliamentary commission will be formed to thrash out the share-out.
The latter point is likely to be contentious. The Ukrainian government fears
that the Russians will use the requirement of the treaty on conventional
forces reduction in Europe - due to be ratified within the next two months -
to insist that it gets the lion's share of conventional weapons.
At present, Ukraine has the bulk of the Commonwealth tank forces on its
territory, and has claimed control over them. Russian military strategists,
however, are calling for a redistribution of the forces based on the size of
the republics - thus giving Russia the majority of the equipment.
The disupte between Russia and the Ukraine over the Black Sea Fleet, by
contrast, may be less contentious - since the indications from Ukraine are
that the government may be content to take a small part of the fleet on
condition that the status of the Crimea, once part of Russia and now a
district of Ukraine, will not be disputed.
Coll Tsaryov said that Russia should propose to the other states that they
can 'contract in' to strategic defence provided by Russia - as for example,
the nuclear early warning system - provided they share the costs and allow
their citizens to serve in strategic forces under Russian command.
He said that Mr Yeltsin agreed with the thrust of the thinking for a Russian
command - but had boxed himself in by 'promises he had to make' that Russia
would be the last to create its own forces. This position was now no longer
tenable, he said
He conceded there was as yet no military doctrine for Russia - saying that
the ideas so far produced by experts had 'talked a lot about peace and
co-operation, but did not define who we thought the likely enemy would be.'
However, he said that a team seconded from the Defence Ministry would begin
work with the parliamentary committee next week.
If the Commonwealth leaders do reject a unified military command tomorrow,
and the process of creation of independent forces begins in earnest, the
Commonwealth will have little further content as an executive body.
The best that can be hoped for is that the states can agree a process of
civilised negotiation on military, as well as on economic and other,
cooperation.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
